   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter" part="N" org="uniform" sample="complete">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-05-30_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>1841
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Hatch-Street-9_IE"
                             instant="false"
                             full="yes"> 9 Hatch Street Dublin</placeName>
                  <date instant="false"/> when="1841-05-30"&gt; cert="high"&gt; 1841 <note anchored="true">May 30</note>
                  <date instant="false"/>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
               Dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2" instant="false" full="yes">friend</persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p part="N">A welcome, more welcome <lb/>
               more delightfully welcome<lb/>
               to me could not have met<lb/>
               my eyes than the note in<lb/>
               your own dear handwriting<lb/>
            </p>
            <p part="N"> I hope it did not give you<lb/>
               horrid pain to write it?<lb/>
               And so much! and so well<lb/>
               written as if you had never<lb/>
               been ill -- whatever it cost you<lb/>
               believe me you have given<lb/>
               me heartfelt pleasure and<lb/>
               more than pleasure - satisfaction.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p part="N">
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH2" instant="false" full="yes">Harriet Beaufort</persName> told you <choice>
                  <orig>yes<lb/>
                     terday </orig>
                  <reg instant="false">yesterday</reg>
               </choice>
               what <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CramP1" instant="false" full="yes">Crampton</persName> says<lb/>
               about the care you ought to take<lb/>
               not to exert yourself or to do any<lb/>
               thing that distresses you standing<lb/>
               sitting -- or moving -- How angry<lb/>
               he would have been had he<lb/>
               four pages in your own hand.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p part="N">Dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2" instant="false" full="yes">mother</persName> thank you<lb/>
               thank you - I will not give you an<lb/>
               opportunity of doing the like again<lb/>
               for I will be with you soon &amp; then<lb/>
               you can only sin by talking or hearing too<lb/>
               much<lb/>
            </p>
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-05-30_page02.jpg"/>
            <p part="N"> I left <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK" instant="false" full="yes">London</placeName> without any anxiety<lb/>
               about <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3" instant="false" full="yes">Fanny</persName> as I had to the very<lb/>
               last day and hour satisfactory<lb/>
               accounts of her progressing - or<lb/>
               or at least of her not back-sliding<lb/>
               I enclose two <hi rend="underline">billet doux</hi>from her<lb/>
               &amp; of her for the pleasure of your<lb/>
               eyes -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p part="N"> I set off from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK" instant="false" full="yes">London</placeName> , from the<lb/>
               Railroad station at 9 oclock - <lb/>
            </p>
            <p part="N">Kind <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1" instant="false" full="yes">Lestock</persName> having brought me<lb/>
               bag &amp; baggage and all to the right<lb/>
               point at the right minute and<lb/>
               there was <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC4" instant="false" full="yes">Charles Fox</persName> ready for me<lb/>
               having taken our two places in the<lb/>
               Coupee - Only costs 2Sh a piece more<lb/>
               than in the 1 <hi rend="superscript">s</hi> class other carriages &amp;<lb/>
               it is delightfully comfortable - as<lb/>
               good as any gentleman's chariot<lb/>
               is or need to be &amp; as dear &amp; large<lb/>
               windows &amp; green curtains &amp; all that<lb/>
               most luxurious <hi rend="underline">exclusive</hi> could want<lb/>
               or wish for excluding sun into the bargain<lb/>
               or not as you like - A most pleasant<lb/>
               journey I had - the easiness of the<lb/>
               motion on the rail way from<placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Birmingham_ENK" instant="false" full="yes">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Birming<lb/>
                     ham </orig>
                     <reg instant="false">Birmingham</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName>
               ham to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Liverpool_ENK" instant="false" full="yes">Liverpool</placeName> resting me complete<lb/>
               ly after the roughness and great<lb/>
               joggling of the rail-road from<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK" instant="false" full="yes">London</placeName> to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Birmingham_ENK" instant="false" full="yes">Birmingham</placeName> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1" instant="false" full="yes">Francis</persName>
               <lb/>
               may remember that I observed this<lb/>
               difference when I travelled with<lb/>
               him &amp; now I have verified it. Tho<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-05-30_page03.jpg"/>
               we came all through in one day<lb/>
               from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK" instant="false" full="yes">London</placeName> to<placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Liverpool_ENK" instant="false" full="yes">Liv.<hi rend="superscript">l</hi>
               </placeName> I was not the<lb/>
               least tired <add instant="false" status="unremarkable">arrived at 1/2 after 5 at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Liverpool_ENK" instant="false" full="yes">Liverpool</placeName>
               </add> - We had but just time<lb/>
               to get from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Liverpool_ENK" instant="false" full="yes">Liv<hi rend="superscript">l</hi>
               </placeName> Rail road station in<lb/>
               fly to steam packet &amp; by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC4" instant="false" full="yes">C Fox's</persName> manual<lb/>
               exertions to get my 4 boxes &amp; 1 bag<lb/>
               &amp; his own (including two rolls of window<lb/>
               curtain chintz of his, so <choice>
                  <orig>barba<lb/>
                     rously </orig>
                  <reg instant="false">barbarously</reg>
               </choice>
               ill done up that they<lb/>
               were forever slipping out<lb/>
               of their <hi rend="underline">silver</hi> paper only covering<lb/>
            </p>
            <p part="N">The Recorder <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ShawF1"
                         cert="high"
                         instant="false"
                         full="yes">F. Shaw</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ConoE1"
                         cert="high"
                         instant="false"
                         full="yes">Col. <hi rend="superscript">l</hi> Conolly</persName> , and<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BethW1" instant="false" full="yes">Sir William Betham</persName> &amp; 2 other members of<lb/>
               parl. (names forgotten) were on board<lb/>
               the packet &amp; gathered round <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC4" instant="false" full="yes">Charles</persName> &amp;<lb/>
               me - and talked an immensity of politics<lb/>
               <del instant="false" status="unremarkable">&amp;c</del>- <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PeelR1" instant="false" full="yes">Peel</persName> and Dissolution &amp;c &amp;c - Literature<lb/>
               &amp; compliments for me interspersed<lb/>
               more than quantum suff - And I<lb/>
               was glad at last even to get down to<lb/>
               my close birth - with 2 quakers &amp; their<lb/>
               bonnets and a lovely contrast <add instant="false" status="unremarkable">in colors</add> - all very quiet<lb/>
               and all fell fast asleep - And nobody<lb/>
               stirred till morning 6 oclock &amp; a very<lb/>
               fine morning and as calm a night<lb/>
               as would be - <del instant="false" status="unremarkable"/>a ten &amp; half hours<lb/>
               passage -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p part="N">
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC4" instant="false" full="yes">C Fox</persName> brought me to this nice house<lb/>
               and dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1" instant="false" full="yes">Harriet</persName> ready dressed at<lb/>
               the door by 1/4 before 8 - and she<lb/>
               welcomed me with her own smiles<lb/>
               and your note - I had had coffee before<lb/>
               I quitted Steampacket - So no hurry for<lb/>
               breakfast &amp; took<persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1" instant="false" full="yes">Harriets</persName> advice &amp; lay<lb/>
               down for half an hour &amp; then washed<lb/>
               &amp; refreshed &amp; no more tired than if I had<lb/>
            </p>
         </div>
